It is known leak, but because a typo it is not getting properly ignored. Fixed by #118 and looks like to be shipped in the next version â€” 1.3.2. 

If you are getting annoyed by this leak you can ignore it. Here is modified snippet from the [docs](https://github.com/square/leakcanary#ignoring-specific-references) that should make the deal.

``` java
public class DebugExampleApplication extends ExampleApplication {
  protected RefWatcher installLeakCanary() {
    ExcludedRefs excludedRefs = AndroidExcludedRefs.createAndroidDefaults()
        .instanceField("android.view.Choreographer$FrameDisplayEventReceiver",
          "mMessageQueue");
        .build();
    return LeakCanary.install(this, DisplayLeakService.class, excludedRefs);
  }
}
```

`ClipboardUIManager` is initialized something like that.

``` java
  public static ClipboardUIManager getInstance(Context context) {
    if (sInstance == null)
      sInstance = new ClipboardUIManager(context);
    return sInstance;
  }
```

Constructor just saves provided context in mContext field. mContext field is only used for `.getSystemService("clipboardEx")` and I think it can be safely swapped with Application context. 

So I think we could call `android.sec.clipboard.ClipboardUIManager.getInstance` with Application object which should prevent activity leaking.

Yes, of course. It's my first app by the way.

```
refWatcher = LeakCanary.install(this);
sInstance = this;
Class cls = Class.forName("android.sec.clipboard.ClipboardUIManager");
Method m = cls.getDeclaredMethod("getInstance",cls);
m.setAccessible(true);
Object o = m.invoke(null, sInstance);
```

Try this:

``` java
refWatcher = LeakCanary.install(this);
mInstance = this;
Class cls = Class.forName("android.sec.clipboard.ClipboardUIManager");
Method m = cls.getDeclaredMethod("getInstance" /*, cls */);
m.setAccessible(true);
Object o = m.invoke(null, mInstance);
```

@GRouslan I'm very sorry for being so late. 

Lol forgot what we are looking for. We are looking for `getInstance(Context context)` method. 
Second (vararg) parameter of `getDeclaredMethod` is used to specify argument types of required method. You are passing `cls` param which is class instance of android.sec.clipboard.ClipboardUIManager. But you need to pass android.content.Context.
So, following snippet should work.

``` java
Class cls = Class.forName("android.sec.clipboard.ClipboardUIManager");
Method m = cls.getDeclaredMethod("getInstance", Context.class);
m.setAccessible(true);
Object o = m.invoke(null, mInstance);
```
